lioncub: Now before I go through this..........let me state what should be a golden rule. If your partner bids a suit in which you have a singleton ......BACKTRACK LIKE CRAZY.  1@C-1@H-?  South you cannot bid 1@S which guarantees a 5-card suit.  THE BID IS DOUBLE.........NEGATIVE.........guaranteeing a 4-card spade suit and tolerance for other suit.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


NT|
lioncub: However after 1@S bid..............W is correct to pass. And of course N should NOT bid 1NT ..........either pass . . . . my choice........or bid 2@C. Now having bid 1NT........should E bid again?|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT|
lioncub: first of all............look at the vulnerability.............one off doubled is 200 worth more than any part score. E should THINK. Partner heard you say 1@H.........and said nothing.  Odds are heavily against bidding again. BUT........having bid 2@D....................S now should crack the whip and double. He should know W has under 3 hearts as he passed. But again ....having passed.......next up is W.|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


NT|
lioncub: RULE IS THIS...........TAKE PARTNER BACK TO FIRST BID SUIT....UNLESS YOU HAVE 2 OR MORE CARDS IN  THE SECOND SUIT THAN YOU DO IN THE FIRST.  So with 3 diamonds and 2 hearts................W should STILL bid 2@H. Here the preference is clear cut........bid 2@H.
